<DATE>
<P>
September 12, 1994, Monday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D2; Page 7; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
874 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA CAREERS; WHERE THE JOBS ARE; HOW TO PAY THE LIGHT BILL 
WHILE WAITING TO BE DISCOVERED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DONNA K. H. WALTERS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 There are two kinds of actors: those who are stars and those who need jobs. 
</P>
<P>
 Stars are the actors who make enough money to tide them over from role to 
role. The legions of character actors, supporting actors, extras and wanna-bes, 
however, find a career in acting is all too often an unconnected series of 
roles separated by a lot of waiting. And they still have to pay the rent. 
</P>
<P>
 The trick is to find a job that pays enough but won't get in the way of 
acting. And that's some trick. 
</P>
<P>
 Actors call the work they do in between acting stints "day jobs," even though 
many are in fact night jobs. Actors waiting tables is an enduring Hollywood 
cliche. But restaurant jobs still work well with an acting career because they 
offer the flexibility to work odd hours or trade shifts with other employees if 
an audition or role comes up. 
</P>
<P>
 Jobs waiting tables are readily available in Southern California and 
well-suited to an actor's skills, said Michael Van Duezer of the Actors Equity 
Assn. "Dealing with the public and all that," he said. "And, depending on where 
you work, it can be good, quick money." 
</P>
<P>
 But, with a little bit of luck and ingenuity, actors can find many other jobs 
to fill the bill. These aren't permanent, full-time positions, so they rarely 
pay well. 
</P>
<P>
 There's no one best job for an actor, said Josh Schiowitz, whose Hollywood 
agency, Schiowitz/Clay/Rose represents established and aspiring actors. 
"Everybody has his own version of the ideal job, one that's flexible, where 
they know you need to take time off for auditions and jobs." 
</P>
<P>
 Some common jobs for actors, because they provide that flexibility, are 
telephone sales, car parking and part-time work at health clubs, construction 
sites and offices. Many actors prefer working for catering brokers -- which 
supply servers and bartenders to caterers or for private parties -- or for 
temporary-help agencies. These days, temp agencies hire for jobs ranging from 
traditional clerical work to accounting, industrial and light construction 
work. 
</P>
<P>
 The best part of working for such agencies is being able to call in and 
specify which days you're willing to work, say actors who choose these jobs. 
</P>
<P>
 Even with the opportunity to work several days or nights a week, many career 
actors find it tough going without a spouse or a roommate to share living 
expenses. 
</P>
<P>
 Todd Hansen is a 29-year-old actor who figures he needs to work three days, or 
nights, in a combination of jobs to earn his fair share of household expenses. 
Sometimes his wife, Midi, wishes he'd work more so they'd have more of a 
cushion in their budget, but Hansen said it's important that he have time to 
devote to the theater group he started and to be available when calls for 
acting work do come. 
</P>
<P>
 Staying available for auditions puts the biggest crimp in an actor's ability 
to work a day job. Sometimes the call comes the night before, but more likely 
only a few hours' notice is given. A missed phone call or audition could be 
some other actor's big break. 
</P>
<P>
 "The other day, a call came at 10 (in the morning) for a 2 o'clock audition," 
said Hansen, who works for Host Helpers, a catering broker, as a 
sometimes-landscaper and does substitute teaching. He made the audition. 
</P>
<P>
 Hansen's most steady money comes from substitute teaching in the Inglewood 
School District, where he can call in once a week and tell a computer what days 
he's available for work. 
</P>
<P>
 "It took a little bit of start-up time to get the paperwork together and pass 
the test" to become credentialed for subbing, but it has been worth it, Hansen 
said. "It's $100 a day and it's only a day." 
</P>
<P>
 Jack Robinson is a fortysomething actor who had a good career going in 
commercial films and minor film and TV roles in Dallas -- including a small one 
in the series "Dallas" -- when he moved his family to Los Angeles five years 
ago in search of larger roles. He says he lives in "eternal hope," but until 
his big break comes, he has had to take a day job. 
</P>
<P>
 Now he works 20 hours a week, at night, reading transcripts to court-reporting 
students at Merit College in Los Angeles. Merit hires primarily actors and 
musicians as readers because of their ability to keep a measured pace while 
reading previously unseen material. Robinson prefers it to waiting tables, but 
wonders whether reading at 240 words per minute -- that's four words a second 
-- is all that beneficial to his acting skills. 
</P>
<P>
 Michelle Holmes is an actor and singer who also works for a small film 
production company. "When all of that fails -- and it's feast or famine -- when 
I need more work, I have one straight world job, or day job," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 Holmes has parlayed her affinity for computers into a consulting job that 
allows her to set her own hours. Currently, she is writing computer-based 
training programs and appearing in a musical, "Song of Singapore," at a Long 
Beach theater. 
</P>
<P>
 Finding an understanding boss is almost as important as finding the right job. 
Agents say it's usually best to be upfront with a perspective employer about 
your acting career, and actors agree. 
</P>
<P>
 One actor recalled having to quit a job where the boss didn't know. "After 
all, there are only so many times you can go home 'sick' in the middle of the 
day" to make an audition, the actor said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
